"Ko M., Shia R.-L., Sze N.-D., Magid H., Bray R.G.","Atmospheric lifetime and global warming potential of HFC-245fa",1999,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","104","D7", 199SJD100097,"8173","8181",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0033586594&partnerID=40&md5=038c0d339cefaff67cf757bdffacd937","Atmosph. and Environ. Research, Inc., Cambridge, MA, United States; AlliedSignal Inc., Buffalo Research Laboratory, Buffalo, NY, United States; AlliedSignal Inc., Research and Technology, Morristown, NJ, United States; Magid Associates, Williamsville, NY, United States; AlliedSignal Inc., Research and Technology, P. O. Box 1021, Morristown, NJ 07962, United States; Atmosph. and Environ. Research, Inc., 840 Memorial Drive, Cambridge, MA 02139, United States; 19 Rockford Place, Williamsville, NY 14221, United States","Ko, M., Atmosph. and Environ. Research, Inc., Cambridge, MA, United States, Atmosph. and Environ. Research, Inc., 840 Memorial Drive, Cambridge, MA 02139, United States; Shia, R.-L., Atmosph. and Environ. Research, Inc., Cambridge, MA, United States, Atmosph. and Environ. Research, Inc., 840 Memorial Drive, Cambridge, MA 02139, United States; Sze, N.-D., Atmosph. and Environ. Research, Inc., Cambridge, MA, United States, Atmosph. and Environ. Research, Inc., 840 Memorial Drive, Cambridge, MA 02139, United States; Magid, H., AlliedSignal Inc., Buffalo Research Laboratory, Buffalo, NY, United States, Magid Associates, Williamsville, NY, United States, 19 Rockford Place, Williamsville, NY 14221, United States; Bray, R.G., AlliedSignal Inc., Research and Technology, Morristown, NJ, United States, AlliedSignal Inc., Research and Technology, P. O. Box 1021, Morristown, NJ 07962, United States","We describe the method used to compute the global warming potential of hydrofluorocarbon (HFC) 245fa (CHF<inf>2</inf>CH<inf>2</inf>CF<inf>3</inf>). The Atmospheric and Environmental Research (AER) two-dimensional (latitude-height) chemistry-transport model was used to calculate the atmospheric lifetime and atmospheric scale height of HFC-245fa. Assuming that reaction with OH is the only removal mechanism, the recommended rate constant from Jet Propulsion Laboratory [1997] (6.1 × 10-13 exp (-1330/T) cm3 s-1) implies a lifetime of 7.6 years and an average atmospheric scale height of 35 km in the stratosphere. Using the IR absorption cross sections for HFC-245fa and CFC-11 determined in the laboratory, the AER one-dimensional radiative-convective model was used to calculate the radiative forcing. The value for HFC-245fa is 1.14 times larger than that for CFC-11 on a mass basis and 1.11 larger on a per molecule basis. The global warming potentials for HFC-245fa (relative to carbon dioxide) are 2400, 760, and 240 (based on the values for absolute global warming potential for carbon dioxide reported by Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change [1996]) at integration time horizons of 20, 100, and 500 years, respectively. Copyright 1999 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"atmospheric chemistry; global warming; greenhouse gas; hydrofluorocarbon; residence time",,,,,,"Bloomfield, P., Inferred lifetimes (1994) NASA Ref. Publ., 1339, pp. 3.1-3.23. , Report on Concentrations, Lifetimes, and Trends of CFCs, Halons, and Related Species, edited by J. Kaye, S. Penkett, and F. Ormond, Jan; Butler, J.H., Elkins, J.W., Thompson, T.M., Hall, B.D., Swanson, T.H., Koropalov, V., Oceanic consumption of CH<inf>3</inf>CCl<inf>3</inf>: Implications for tropospheric OH (1991) J. Geophys. Res., 96, pp. 22,347-22,355; Chen, J., Young, V., Niki, H., Magid, H., Kinetic and mechanistic studies for reactions of CF<inf>3</inf>CH<inf>2</inf>CHF<inf>2</inf> (HFC-245fa) initiated by H-atom abstraction using atomic chlorine (1997) J. Phys. Chem. A, 101, pp. 2648-2653; Christidis, N., Hurley, M.D., Pinnock, S., Shine, K.P., Wallington, T.J., Radiative forcing of climate change by CFC-11 and possible CFC replacements (1997) J. Geophys. Res., 102, pp.